The goal of this strategy has, presumably, been to sell more iPhones, thus =
maximizing the addressable market for Apple services, but that doesn't seem=
 to be working. Apple doesn't disclose iPhone unit sales, but given that no=
minal pricing has remained the same it seems safe to assume that iPhone uni=
t sales are basically holding steady:

It's impossible to prove a counterfactual of course; it may be the case tha=
t the iPhone's decreasing real price has stopped a significant decline in u=
nit sales. I think it's more likely, however, that iPhone demand is pretty =
inelastic: if you want a new phone you're going to get one, and Apple's mar=
ketshare is what it is. And, to the extent that is the case, Apple is argua=
bly leaving money on the table by not increasing iPhone prices to at least =
keep pace with inflation.

Still, even with inflation accounted for, the 16e is still more expensive t=
han its predecessors at the low end. There's another factor to consider, th=
ough: tariffs. The recent 10% tariffs President Trump levied on all Chinese=
 goods does not =E2=80=94 in contrast to the tariffs in his first term =E2=
=80=94 have an exception for iPhones.

Tariffs are levied on the landed price of products, which is typically the =
invoice from the manufacturer plus freight and insurance costs; if we assum=
e that Apple wants a 45% margin on every iPhone it sells, that necessitates=
 a $21 price increase over the original iPhone SE:

* 1st Gen SE price: $532
* Target margin: $239
* Landed price: $207
* Tariffs: $21
* Total: $553

Now we're within $46, or a bit more than half that amount to cover signific=
antly upgraded components =E2=80=94 including Face ID, much more storage, a=
nd an A18 chip =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Apple wants to keep their margins.

Apple Intelligence Table Stakes
-------------------------------

There's one more factor =E2=80=94 which may ultimately invalidate the entir=
e last section! =E2=80=94 and I think it has to do with the name change fro=
m SE to 16e: the latter suggests that this iPhone will be upgraded somewhat=
 regularly. To that end, note Apple's current lineup:

Price Chip iPhone 16 Pro $999 A18 Pro iPhone 16 $799 A18 iPhone 15 $699 A16=
 iPhone 16e $599 A18

If Apple followed their normal pattern than the iPhone 15 would drop by $10=
0 next year, matching the current 16e price. In fact, I think the iPhone 15=
 will be discontinued, for one obvious reason: the A16 chip doesn't support=
 Apple Intelligence. Indeed, notice that Apple's marketing pages place the =
iPhone 16e above the iPhone 15 even though it is less expensive and lacks f=
eatures like MagSafe or dual-cameras:

Honestly, I'm kind of surprised Apple didn't just discontinue the iPhone 15=
 along with the iPhone 14; I expect that to happen this fall when the iPhon=
e 16 will drop to $699, while the iPhone 16e will probably stick at $599.

Price Chip iPhone 17 Pro $999 A19 Pro iPhone 17 $799 A19 iPhone 16 $699 A18=
 iPhone 16e $599 A18

Then, a year after that, things may be back to "normal", with a lineup that=
 looks something like this:

Price Chip iPhone 18 Pro $999 A20 Pro iPhone 18 $799 A20 iPhone 17 $699 A19=
 iPhone 16 $599 A18 iPhone 16e $499 A18

After that comes the update to the iPhone 17e =E2=80=94 and in that world, =
the iPhone 16e might still be around!

Price Chip iPhone 19 Pro $999 A21 Pro iPhone 19 $799 A21 iPhone 18 $699 A20=
 iPhone 17 $599 A19 iPhone 17e $499 A19 iPhone 16e $399 A18

The key factor undergirding this analysis is the recognition that Apple see=
s Apple Intelligence support as table stakes for its entire lineup going fo=
rward; the problem is that Apple just couldn't figure out a way to have a p=
owerful enough phone that hit the traditional SE price point, so the compan=
y is resetting the lineup for the next couple of years, and eventually chea=
per iPhones may be back.

Honestly, I think this is the more compelling explanation for the 16e's pri=
ce; Apple wants to sell more devices to drive more services, and cheaper iP=
hones help with that. For now, however, Apple Intelligence across the lineu=
p is a bigger priority.

Apple vs. U.K, Continued
------------------------

From the Washington Post ( https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2025/0=
2/21/apple-yanks-encrypted-storage-uk-instead-allowing-backdoor-access/ ) :

Apple disabled its most secure data storage offering for new customers in B=
ritain on Friday rather than comply with a secret government order that wou=
ld have allowed police and intelligence agencies to access the encrypted co=
ntent. The order under the country=E2=80=99s Investigatory Powers Act, repo=
rted by The Washington Post ( https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/202=
5/02/07/apple-encryption-backdoor-uk/ ) two weeks ago, requires the Califor=
nia maker of iPhones and Mac computers to create a backdoor capability allo=
wing authorities to snoop on iCloud storage anywhere in the world.

That would nullify the technology in Apple=E2=80=99s Advanced Data Protecti=
on service, which provides such strong encryption that the company itself i=
s unable to retrieve users=E2=80=99 information. Apple rolled out that opti=
onal end-to-end encryption globally starting in late 2022=E2=80=A6British c=
ustomers who already have Advanced Data Protection will be warned later to =
disable it or lose access to iCloud.

